  "output": "That's a minor detail — I have enough to give a solid, actionable report without it.\n\n## Performance Analysis: jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async pipeline (`fetchers.py` → `filters.py` → `store.py`), not a web frontend — no React exists in this repo (no `package.json`, no `.jsx`/`.tsx`). I've mapped your categories onto their real equivalents: SQL N+1 → literal N+1 query pattern found; React re-renders → N/A; caching → HTTP pagination/fetch caching; redundant computations → regex/hash recompilation.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every fetched job, a separate `SELECT` hits SQLite in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n```\n\nWith thousands of jobs per run (Apple ~6,400 roles, Amazon/Microsoft boards likewise large), that's thousands of round-trip `execute()` calls for what should be one lookup.\n\n**Fix** — batch the existence/hash check into a single query, then loop over the in-memory dict:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i+900]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\",\n            chunk).fetchall())\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns N queries into 1 (or a handful, chunked for the `IN` clause limit).\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside** that per-job call:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job!\n```\n\nFor N jobs and K keywords, that's N×K regex compilations instead of K. With thousands of jobs and a real keyword list, this dominates filter runtime for no reason.\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locs = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                       locations=locs, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(and change `match()`'s `include`/`exclude` params to accept pre-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` directly, dropping the `_compile` calls inside it).\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies `raw` just to discard it — `models.py:71-75`\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # recursively deep-copies EVERY field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then throws the copy away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively walks and copies nested dict/list values. Most fetchers stash the full source payload in `raw` (e.g. Greenhouse departments list, Lever categories, Ashby compensation blob). Every insert/update pays to copy that structure before immediately discarding it — pure waste, and it happens for every new/changed job every run.\n\n**Fix** — build the row dict directly instead of going through `asdict`:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range,\n        \"key\": self.key, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\n### 4. Redundant computation — `content_hash` (SHA-256) computed twice per job — `store.py:67` + `models.py:75`\n\n`diff()` reads `job.content_hash` once to compare against the DB, then `_insert`/`_update` call `job.to_row()`, which recomputes the same SHA-256 via the `content_hash` property again. It's a cheap hash, but it's genuinely duplicated work on every insert/update path, and easy to eliminate:\n\n```python\n# in diff(), reuse the value instead of recomputing inside to_row()\nh = job.content_hash\nif prev_hash is None:\n    new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now, h)\nelif prev_hash != h:\n    changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now, h)\n```\nand have `_insert`/`_update` accept the precomputed hash rather than pulling it from `to_row()` again.\n\n### 5. Missed concurrency — sequential pagination inside a single source — `fetchers.py` (Workday, Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, Netflix, Optiver, Two Sigma, ByteDance, Phenom)\n\nEvery paginated fetcher does a `for/while` loop awaiting one page at a time:\n\n```python\nfor pg in range(max_pages):\n    data = await _get_json(client, url, params={..., \"start\": pg * 10}, ...)\n```\n\n`fetch_all` parallelizes **across** sources (semaphore=8) but each source's own pages are strictly serial. Workday alone caps at offset 5000 / page_size 20 = up to 250 sequential requests for one company. Apple/Amazon/Microsoft can hit dozens of pages too.\n\n**Fix (where the API reports a total up front)** — fetch page 1, read the total/count, then fire the rest concurrently:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_workday(client, source):\n    ...\n    first = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={**body0, \"offset\": 0}, ...)\n    total = first.get(\"total\", 0)\n    jobs = [...parse first page...]\n    remaining_offsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\n    sem = asyncio.Semaphore(6)\n    async def fetch_page(off):\n        async with sem:\n            return await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\",\n                                    json={**body0, \"offset\": off}, ...)\n    pages = await asyncio.gather(*(fetch_page(o) for o in remaining_offsets))\n    for data in pages:\n        jobs.extend(...)\n    return jobs\n```\n\nThis is the single biggest wall-clock win available — a 250-page Workday board goes from ~250 sequential round trips to ~40 batches of 6 concurrent ones (bounded by a per-source semaphore so you don't hammer one host). Apply the same pattern anywhere the first response exposes a total (Amazon `total_hits`, Phenom `totalHits`, Eightfold has `count` in some responses — verify per-API before assuming).\n\nWhere the API doesn't expose a total up front (Google's scraped `ds:1` blob, Apple's hydration blob, D. E. Shaw), the current \"stop on first page with nothing new\" early-exit is already the right, cheap strategy — no change needed there.\n\n### 6. No conditional-GET / ETag reuse across scheduled runs\n\nThe project runs on a 12h schedule (per `6ae8083`), and every run does a full unpaginated-to-completion fetch of every board from scratch — no `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, even though `httpx.AsyncClient` makes this trivial to add. Most of these bespoke ATS endpoints (GraphQL, JSON widgets) won't honor conditional headers, but the plain REST ones (Greenhouse `boards-api`, Lever `api.lever.co`, SmartRecruiters, Workable) are CDN-fronted and likely do. Worth spot-checking response headers (`ETag`/`Last-Modified`) on those four and, if present, short-circuiting with a 304 to skip the parse+diff entirely when nothing changed.\n\n### Not applicable / no issues found\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend framework in this repo.\n- **Memory leaks**: this is a short-lived CLI process per run (`asyncio.run`, `httpx.AsyncClient` closed via `try/finally` in `fetch_all`, SQLite connection closed via `Store.__exit__`) — nothing long-running enough to leak in the traditional sense.\n\n### Priority order\n1. **#1 (store N+1)** — highest impact, straightforward, changes a real bottleneck as job volume grows.\n2. **#5 (sequential pagination)** — biggest wall-clock win, especially for Workday/Amazon/Apple boards.\n3. **#2 (regex recompilation)** — cheap fix, meaningful CPU savings on large job counts.\n4. **#3/#4 (asdict/hash duplication)** — smaller wins, worth doing while touching `store.py`/`models.py` for #1.\n5. **#6 (conditional GET)** — exploratory; only pursue after confirming which endpoints actually support it.\n",
